title: Koush did it again
comment: Works great. Nice, clean UI. People uninstalling and complaining should understand how superuser works. There are two components of superuser: the UI app and the binary su. The binary su would asks the UI each time it's invoked by root apps for root permission. So, before uninstalling the UI app, be sure to install another superuser app first and be sure the new superuser app installs its own su binary and works ok,  then uninstall Clockworkmod superuser app.

comment: Note 2.  This app does not uninstall cleanly.  Like some other users have mentioned.  I would class this as AdWare or at the very least MalWare.  Once uninstalled any "Super User" activity is directed to the Google App web page.  It also does not play well with other "Super User" software, and gave no warning about that issue.  Still trying to extract it from my phone.  My own fault should have waited for other reviews ... it was too good to be true.  Version installed was dated 2013-03-04.  OK Managed to uninstall.  Bit of a palaver ... 1. reinstall Superuser ... and remove itsn't need to require superuser access, and set to "prompt" - as it seems to ask at times anyway.  2 reinstall previous app (SuperSU), 3. Remove super user rights to Superuser.  4. Uninstall "Superuser".  5. ReBoot.  6. SuperSU may request update or reinstall ... do as requested. 7.  Reboot.   8. Phew, breath a sigh of relief.    No promises that this exact method will work for you, but I think you get the drift on what to do.  Now I can get some sleep.  Like the idea of this app.  But it isn't there yet, and shouldn't be on the app store imo.  Keep on going, you'll get there.
